# Fixture IRI-002: pure fragment reference resolution
#
# RFC 3986 §5.2.2: when R is a pure-fragment reference (`#foo`), the
# algorithm sets T.scheme = Base.scheme, T.authority = Base.authority,
# T.path = Base.path, T.query = Base.query, T.fragment = R.fragment.
# The base path — INCLUDING any path component — is preserved.
#
# The base IRI below contains a fragment `#section1`; that must be
# REPLACED by the reference fragment, not concatenated.
#
# Hypothesis: An implementation that strips the base fragment before
# resolution but then re-appends the old base fragment when R.fragment
# is non-empty will double-apply: producing
# `http://example/doc#section1section2` or similar.  The correct result
# is `http://example/doc#section2`.
#
# A second failure mode: an implementation that drops the base path when
# resolving a pure-fragment will produce `http://example#section2`
# instead of `http://example/doc#section2`.
#
# Spec: RFC 3986 §5.2.2 (reference resolution algorithm, R.fragment branch)

@base <http://example/doc#section1> .
@prefix p: <http://example.org/pred/> .

# Must resolve to http://example/doc#section2  (NOT double-fragment)
<#section2>  p:describes "pure-fragment-reference" .

# Must resolve to http://example/doc  (empty fragment — no fragment component)
<#>  p:describes "empty-fragment" .
